  "description": "Learn to identify nearby objects using the demonstrative pronoun هَذَا (this) with masculine nouns.",
  "vocabulary": ["word-001", "word-002", "word-003", "word-004", "word-005", "word-006", "word-007", "word-008", "word-009"],
  "grammarPoints": ["gp-001", "gp-002"],
  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "Basic Demonstratives and Indefiniteness",
      "titleArabic": "اسم الإشارة والتنكير",
      "content": [
        "This lesson introduces the demonstrative pronoun هَذَا (this) for masculine nouns. It is pronounced 'hādhā' but written without the initial alif.",
        "Arabic has no copula - there is no word for 'is'. The sentence هَذَا كِتَابٌ literally translates to 'this book' but means 'this is a book'.",
        "There is no separate indefinite article like 'a/an' in English. Instead, tanwīn (the -n sound at the end of nouns) indicates indefiniteness."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "هَذَا is used for masculine singular nouns (this)",
        "Arabic sentences don't require 'is' - subject and predicate are simply placed together",
        "Tanwīn (-ٌ, -ً, -ٍ) marks indefinite nouns",
        "The interrogative particle أَ at the beginning turns statements into yes/no questions"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "مَا هَذَا؟", "english": "What is this?" },
        { "arabic": "هَذَا كِتَابٌ", "english": "This is a book" },
        { "arabic": "أَهَذَا بَيْتٌ؟", "english": "Is this a house?" },
        { "arabic": "نَعَم، هَذَا بَيْتٌ", "english": "Yes, this is a house" },
        { "arabic": "لَا، هَذَا مَسْجِدٌ", "english": "No, this is a mosque" }
      ]
    }
  ],
